<DOC><DOCNO> AP880917-0148 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1817EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-17 0453</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0463</SECOND><HEAD>Storm Spawns Tornadoes In Texas, Rain in Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Hurricane Gilbert produced dozens of tornadoes in eastern Texason Saturday as it weakened and was downgraded to a tropicaldepression, and it continued to push rain and thunderstorms acrossthe southern Plains.   Eight tornadoes touched down in the San Antonio, Texas, area andthree near Del Rio, Texas. Twisters also touched down near theTexas communities of Devine, Jourdanton, Fischer, Sattler and Brady.   Saturday afternoon, Gilbert's center was about 230 mileswest-southwest of Brownsville, Texas, on the Texas-Mexico border.   Rain and thunderstorms extended across the southern Plains andinto eastern Arkansas, northern Mississippi and northern Alabama,the Appalachians, from Florida across New York state and westernNew England.   Rain also was scattered over northwest Montana.   Rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 2.10inches at Bluefield, W.Va.; 1.96 inches at the Air Force Base nearSan Antonio; 0.84 of an inch at Greer, S.C.; and 0.83 of an inch atHickory, N.C.   A winter storm watch was posted for Saturday night and Sundayfor western and central Montana. Cold rain was expected to becomelocally heavy snow in the mountains and passes. As much as 8 inchesof snow was expected over the southwest and central mountains bySunday, with up to a foot of new snow in the higher mountains.   The cold and rain also were expected to reach across northernWyoming and snowfall of 2 to 5 inches was possible in the mountainsof northern Wyoming, including the Yellostone National Park area.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42degrees at both Cutbank and Great Falls, Mont., to 96 degrees atPalm Springs, Calif. The nation's low Saturday was 22 degrees atGunnison, Colo.   Sunday's forecast was for rain and thunderstorms from theeastern two-thirds of Texas across Oklahoma and eastern Kansas,from northern Arkansas across Iowa, Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana,northwest Kentucky, western Tennessee, northern Mississippi,Alabama, Georgia and northwest Florida. Showers also were expectedfrom Maine across east-central New England and thunderstorms wereto extend from Montana across Wyoming into the western portion ofthe northern Plains, with rain becoming snow in the mountains.   High temperatures were to be in the 40s and 50s over thenorthern half of the Rockies and the upper Missouri Valley. Highsin the 60s and 70s were forecast from New England across NewJersey, the northern Appalachians, the remainder of the upperMidwest and Rockies and the Pacific Northwest, with 70s along theCalifornia coast. Temperatures were to reach the low 90s inFlorida, southern Mississippi and Louisiana, and from southwestTexas through the desert Southwest, with 80s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>